  "teacher_notes": [
    "Emphasize that \\(\\sqrt{a^2} = |a|\\) (absolute value), not just \\(a\\). This is crucial when dealing with variables that could be negative.",
    "Students must learn to recognize perfect squares up to at least 225 (\\(15^2\\)). This makes simplification much faster.",
    "Common error: thinking \\(\\sqrt{a + b} = \\sqrt{a} + \\sqrt{b}\\). This is FALSE! Always emphasize: the square root distributes over multiplication/division, NOT addition/subtraction.",
    "When simplifying radicals, always look for the largest perfect square factor to minimize work.",
    "For combining radicals: only like radicals (same number under the radical) can be added or subtracted, just like combining like terms in algebra."
  ]
}
